05684nam a22008895i 9780231546171DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018009493  a97802315461717 a10.7312/diag185462doi  a(DE-B1597)502715  a(OCoLC)1048896426  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBP163b.D5213 2018 4aBP163b.D5213 2018eb 7aPHI0120002bisacsh04a181/.072231 aDiagne, Souleymane Bachir, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOpen to Reason :bMuslim Philosophers in Conversation with the Western Tradition /cSouleymane Bachir Diagne. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion, Culture, and Public Life ;v3600tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. And How to Not Philosophize? -- t2. How a Language Becomes Philosophical -- t3. What Does It Mean for a Philosophy to Be Islamic? -- t4. Against Philosophy? -- t5. A Lesson In Ecological Philosophy -- t6. The Obligation to Philosophize -- t7. The Need for Philosophy -- t8. The Philosophy of Reform -- t9. The Philosophy of Movement -- t10. Pluralism -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat does it mean to be a Muslim philosopher, or to philosophize in Islam? In Open to Reason, Souleymane Bachir Diagne traces Muslims’ intellectual and spiritual history of examining and questioning beliefs and arguments to show how Islamic philosophy has always engaged critically with texts and ideas both inside and outside its tradition. Through a rich reading of classical and modern Muslim philosophers, Diagne explains the long history of philosophy in the Islamic world and its relevance to crucial issues of our own time.From classical figures such as Avicenna to the twentieth-century Sufi master and teacher of tolerance Tierno Bokar Salif Tall, Diagne explores how Islamic thinkers have asked and answered such questions as Does religion need philosophy? How can religion coexist with rationalism? What does it mean to interpret a religious narrative philosophically? What does it mean to be human, and what are human beings’ responsibilities to nature? Is there such a thing as an “Islamic” state, or should Muslims reinvent political institutions that suit their own times? Diagne shows that philosophizing in Islam in its many forms throughout the centuries has meant a commitment to forward and open thinking. A remarkable history of philosophy in the Islamic world as well as a work of philosophy in its own right, this book seeks to contribute to the revival of a spirit of pluralism rooted in Muslim intellectual and spiritual traditions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aIslam and philosophy. 0aIslamic philosophy. 0aPhilosophy and religion. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aAdjemian, Jonathan.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2016-2018z978311066255908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Package 2018z978311065486808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2018z978311060660708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2018 Englishz978311060421408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2018z9783110603217oZ